  "text": "Apache Kafka implements a comprehensive Startable/Stoppable service lifecycle pattern across its broker, controller, and Connect framework components.\n\n## Core Lifecycle Interface\n\nThe foundation of the service lifecycle pattern is defined in **kafka/server/Server.scala**, which provides the Server trait with three core methods:\n- startup(): Unit - Initiates server startup\n- shutdown(): Unit - Initiates server shutdown  \n- awaitShutdown(): Unit - Waits for shutdown completion\n\nThe trait also defines ProcessStatus states: SHUTDOWN, STARTING, STARTED, and SHUTTING_DOWN, which track the lifecycle state machine.\n\n## Service Startup and Shutdown Ordering\n\n**KafkaRaftServer (kafka/server/KafkaRaftServer.scala)** orchestrates the dependent service startup and shutdown:\n- **Startup order (lines 90-98)**: Controller starts first, then broker\n  ```\n  controller.foreach(_.startup())\n  broker.foreach(_.startup())\n  ```\n- **Shutdown order (lines 100-107)**: Broker stops first (reverse order), then controller\n  ```\n  broker.foreach(_.shutdown())\n  controller.foreach(_.shutdown())\n  ```\n\nThis reverse-order shutdown ensures dependent services stop in the correct sequence. The shutdown happens in this order because the controller may be needed for controlled shutdown of the broker.\n\n## Broker Lifecycle Implementation\n\n**BrokerServer (kafka/server/BrokerServer.scala)** provides an extensive startup sequence (lines 189-607) that initializes components in dependency order:\n1. Shared server startup\n2. Scheduler initialization\n3. Log manager and metadata cache creation\n4. Lifecycle manager creation\n5. Socket server and request handlers\n6. Replica manager\n7. Coordinators (group, transaction, share)\n8. Various managers and publishers\n\nThe shutdown method (lines 729-843) carefully dismantles services in reverse order using CoreUtils.swallow() for fault-tolerant shutdown, ensuring one failure doesn't prevent other services from shutting down.\n\n## Shared Infrastructure Coordination\n\n**SharedServer (kafka/server/SharedServer.scala)** manages components shared between broker and controller with reference counting:\n- startForBroker() and startForController() methods handle conditional startup\n- Proper synchronization ensures single initialization despite multiple callers\n- stopForBroker() and stopForController() enable coordinated shutdown\n\n## Broker State Management\n\n**BrokerLifecycleManager (kafka/server/BrokerLifecycleManager.scala)** manages the broker's lifecycle state with:\n- Event queue paradigm for sequential state transitions\n- Future-based coordination for startup/shutdown milestones\n- Registration and heartbeat management with controller\n- Methods: beginControlledShutdown(), beginShutdown() for graceful transitions\n\n## Connect Framework Lifecycle Pattern\n\nThe Kafka Connect framework implements parallel lifecycle patterns:\n\n**Herder interface (org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/Herder.java)** defines start() and stop() methods for the main coordinator of worker and connector lifecycle.\n\n**StatusBackingStore interface (org/apache/kafka/connect/storage/StatusBackingStore.java)** provides start() and stop() for dependent services managing connector/task status.\n\n**AbstractHerder (org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/AbstractHerder.java)** implements lifecycle coordination:\n- startServices() (lines 180-184): Starts worker, status backing store, config backing store in order\n- stopServices() (lines 186-192): Stops in reverse order with cleanup:\n  1. statusBackingStore.stop()\n  2. configBackingStore.stop()\n  3. worker.stop()\n  4. connectorExecutor.shutdown()\n  5. connectorClientConfigOverridePolicyPlugin close\n\n**StandaloneHerder (org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/standalone/StandaloneHerder.java)** implements the concrete lifecycle:\n- start() (lines 110-114): Calls startServices() to initialize all dependencies\n- stop() (lines 117-130): Cleanly stops all connectors, then calls stopServices() in reverse order\n\n## Key Lifecycle Patterns\n\n1. **Dependent Service Ordering**: Services with dependencies start after their dependencies and stop before them\n2. **Status State Machine**: Explicit state transitions prevent invalid operations and enable monitoring\n3. **Reverse-Order Shutdown**: Shutdown sequence reverses startup sequence to maintain invariants\n4. **Fault-Tolerant Cleanup**: CoreUtils.swallow() ensures one failure doesn't prevent other shutdown tasks\n5. **Future-Based Coordination**: CompletableFuture enables waiting for asynchronous startup/shutdown milestones\n6. **Event Queue Paradigm**: Sequential processing prevents race conditions in state transitions"
}

